The RPK is a 7.62x39mm light machine gun of Soviet design, developed by Mikhail Kalashnikov in the late 1950s, parallel with the AKM assault rifle. title: For Sale:  500 Sierra MatchKing .22cal 77gr. MK 262 Bullets
postcontent:
One sealed box of 500 Sierra .22 caliber 77 grain MatchKing OTM bullets with cannelure. These are the very same bullets loaded in Black Hills MK 262 Mod 1 Ammo, which is some of the best 5.56x45mm NATO ammo ever to come in a battle pack. Black Hills Ammunition worked for years, first with the U.S. Army Marksmanship Unit (AMU) and later the U.S. Navy, on a long-term project that resulted in MK 262 Mod 1. Civilian shooters can now hand load that exact same round for improved downrange performance, accuracy, and lethality. The MK 262 Mod 1 projectile is an open-tipped match (OTM) bullet, though it does not expand in the manner of a conventional hollowpoint. In fact, the hollow cavity is not there to induce expansion; it’s there to put the majority of weight towards the projectile’s rear so that it is more stable in flight and increase accuracy. When the bullet strikes soft tissue, the heavier base comes around and causes the bullet to yaw, or tumble. The hollow nose cone breaks off and often the bullet fragments at the cannelure. This happens across a wide range of the velocity spectrum, which is why MK 262 Mod 1 proved effective in SBRs in addition to the longer-barreled SPRs. I spoke with a friend who has had multiple combat tours in both Iraq and Afghanistan. His experiences as both a Special Forces sniper team leader and assaulter offered a unique perspective on ammo performance. As a sniper, MK 262 was his preferred round (when he was not using 7.62x51mm NATO), and he said simply, “It’s the best, most accurate round the Army has ever issued". 
 This is currently selling for over $140 at Midway. (plus shipping and tax which will easily put you over $150)
Please see my other auction for powder, and primers.
 Cash only please,  I do my best to answer emails/questions etc. ASAP. Thanks!

title: For Sale:  Competion .22 rifle on the cheap
postcontent:
I was primarily a competitive handgun shooter for 30 years and I also love to shoot my AR15. At the range I met this guy and his 13 year old daughter who had a pair of custom modified Ruger 10/22's. I was in awe to watch this young girl shoot dime sized groups at 80 yards. They let me shoot theirs and I was hooked. That was until they told me how much was in their guns price wise. For a good competitive Ruger (with all the fun stuff) you'll be over a grand. At the time I had just put the finishing touches on my AR15 and my $600 gun is now a $2800 gun. So when I told my wife about spending another grand or more on a .22, needless to say she had a fit. That's when I got the bright idea to see if I could modify my Marlin. It was always a great gun but had the crappy original trigger at 7 lbs. I found this guy up in Illinois who is an expert on model 60's and sent my gun to him to work on. He is the only one in the country that has a patented after market trigger for the model 60. It's two stage flat trigger  breaks around 12 ounces. I also had him go through the gun and polish the charger and ramp, replace springs and what not. Then I put the synthetic stock and and custom charging handle on it. Shoots like a dream.
All that being said I eventually got the Ruger I wanted but it cost me $1300. A lot run double that for the VERY serious competitors.
I believe that the Marlin is a great starter gun for someone who wants to learn the basics about .22 competition shooting.
If money is not an issue I would go with the Ruger but if you want to make sure you or a loved one is serious and will stick with it before you sink a grand into a gun, consider the Marlin.
Comes with custom Katz 2 stage trigger that breaks at 12oz to 1lb, ATI Marlin Fiberforce Stock and Custom stainless steel, gnarled charging handle. Also included is the original Walnut stock with the Squirrels on both sides, carrying case and a Tasco World Class 3x9x40 Scope.

title: For Sale:  G 43 DUV "WWII" Nazi Marked 8MM
postcontent: a late WWII G43 semi-automatic rifle as produced by Berlin-Lubecker (duv)fitted with the correct WWII ZF4 scope mounts. The receiver is a rough forged/machined version that is marked on the left side with an "eagle Waffenamt" proof ahead of the serial number, a Nazi firing proof followed by "G. 43 duv 44.The stock is the laminated version and the handguard is the early red resin "Bakelite" version manufactured by DUROFOL The Gewehr 43 is a 7.92×57mm Mauser caliber semi-automatic rifle developed by Nazi Germany during World War II. It was a modification of the earlier G41(W), using an improved gas system similar to that of the Soviet Tokarev SVT-40 The Gewehr 43 was put into production in October 1943, and followed in 1944 by the Karabiner 43 (K43), which was identical to the G43 in every way except for the letter stamped on the side.

title: For Sale:  OSS Suppressor 5.56 BPR1 & SRM4
postcontent:
The next generation of suppressors. OSS Misson has changed the world of suppressors with the introduction of their modular suppressor system. This innovative design combines the best of sound reduction, back pressure elimination and consistent point of impact.

The BPR1 is an over the barrel suppressor with several revolutionary capabilities. Instead of just trapping the expanding gases inside a baffle, the OSS BPR1 controls their expansion. This function virtually eliminates excessive backpressure that ALL current generation cans produce. In short, this means you can attach the OSS can to your AR rifle and experience virtually 0 gas blow back. No more tuning your gas system for use with a can. The OSS can also eliminates the increased rate of fire on select fire weapons, prevents excessive fouling due to increased back pressure, and allows the gun to operate as if there was no can attached. This reduced back pressure prevents toxic gases and excessive lead particulates from being forced into your face.

The BPR1 also has a patented self-tightening function. Every time the weapon fire, the device tightens. It is impossible to loosen the OSS BPR system through shooting.

The over barrel design of the BPR1 means you are adding minimal weight to the front of your weapon. Instead of attaching a 7 inch can to the end, you are essentially only extending your overall length by 3.9 inches. But don't be fooled by other over barrel designs. The OSS an controls the expansion of gases with the entire length of the can thanks to their patented design. This over barrel design keeps the weapon balanced which helps the operator control the weapon and prevent fatigue.

The last piece to the puzzle is the OSS SRM4 (signature reduction module). As the name implies, this device is designed and engineered to reduce the visual and audio signature even further than a traditional can. The SRM is attached inline to the BPR. And like the BRP system, the outer housing can be removed for caliber conversion.

The over barrel design does require a 14.5" or longer barrel.

Anyone who is a serious buyer and wants to meet for a Demo, I can arrange that. I am located in the east valley and will travel within Phoenix area.

Price is $1150 for the full 5.56 system.
